<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="105" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="105">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="16" pageNumber="105">
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconiella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconiella corylina" order="Diaporthales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="corylina">Melanconiella corylina</taxonomicName>
is associated with canker disease of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Corylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Corylus mandshurica" order="Fagales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mandshurica">Corylus mandshurica</taxonomicName>
in China. It can be distinguished from its closest relative, the generic type 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spodiaea" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" rank="species" species="spodiaea">M. spodiaea</taxonomicName>
growing in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Carpinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Carpinus" order="Fagales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Carpinus</taxonomicName>
spp., by its hyaline, discosporina-like conidia, and the smaller size of conidia (8-13.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-4 vs.&gt; 13.3-15.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7.5-8.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) as well as the hosts (
<bibRefCitation author="Voglmayr, H" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 44" title="Multigene phylogeny and taxonomy of the genus Melanconiella (Diaporthales)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-012-0175-8" volume="57" year="2012">Voglmayr et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconiella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconiella flavovirens" order="Diaporthales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="flavovirens">Melanconiella flavovirens</taxonomicName>
also occurs on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Corylus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Corylus" order="Fagales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Corylus</taxonomicName>
(in Europe and North America), and it can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. corylina" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" rank="species" species="corylina">M. corylina</taxonomicName>
based on larger conidia (12-15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.0-5.5 vs.&gt; 8-13.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×2.5–">x2.5-</normalizedToken>
4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Voglmayr, H" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 44" title="Multigene phylogeny and taxonomy of the genus Melanconiella (Diaporthales)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-012-0175-8" volume="57" year="2012">Voglmayr et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). The phylogenetic inferences indicated 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. corylina" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" rank="species" species="corylina">M. corylina</taxonomicName>
as an individual well-supported clade (MP/ML/BI=100/99/1) within 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" family="Melanconidaceae" genus="Melanconiella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanconiella" order="Diaporthales" pageId="16" pageNumber="105" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Melanconiella</taxonomicName>
and we therefore describe it as new, based on sequence data and morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
